IBM History: From Cheese Knife to Space Flight.
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago. Its original name "Calculating, Tabulating, Recording Corporation" was quite complicated.
It took the name IBM in 1924. It was originally called the brand, which was used for the company's offices in Canada and South America.
The foundations of the future IBM were laid by the merger of four companies, the history of which begins in the 1880s.
They owned technology, such as the legendary "table clock", i.e. clocks that record the time when employees come and go from work.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlet Flint, who also headed the board of trustees of the company until 1930.
Flint hired a rival company director, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
Then the head pushed the founder of IBM into the shadows - Watson's ideas remain the basis of an unshakable corporate culture and individuality.
Watson headed the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began with the manufacture and sale of various equipment for business - from cheese knives and meat cutters to cash registers.
During Watson's first four years in office, revenue doubled to $9 million, and the company began a massive expansion to all continents.
Watson became so important to the company that almost forty years later his place in the chair of the director was taken by his son, Thomas Watson Jr.
Under his leadership, IBM began to develop artificial intelligence technologies and created the first programming language.
In the 1960s, both IBM employees and computers helped NASA control spaceflights — to Mercury, Saturn, and 1969 — the human flight to the moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers, the IBM Line System/360.
The classic PC that defined the computer standards of the time, called IBM 5150, appeared on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold the production of computers to the Chinese company Lenovo, at the same time buying the consulting department of PricewaterhouseCoopers, thus fully concentrating on consulting and high-value-added services.
Over the past three years, IBM has made great strides with its Smarter Planet concept.
Its aim is to make reasonable use of technology in areas where it has not yet been planned, and to improve the road situation and urban governance.
In the area of commerce, IBM recently introduced the Smarter Commerce platform, which helps businessmen control the entire trading cycle.
IBM’s tradition is strong even in our country.
In the former Czechoslovakia, as the first country located simultaneously in central and eastern Europe, IBM founded its branch in 1932.
Today, IBM CZ also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
Central and Eastern Europe is headquartered in Prague, where a world-class speech recognition research group also operates.
