21st Century House in Vienna
Pavilion in a new place
Ingeborg Winsowski
An architectural history with ups, downs and a happy ending. Austria's pavilion for the 1958 World's Fair in Brussels won prizes, became a museum in Vienna, was empty and was abandoned.
It is now being re-opened as an exhibition center.
The Austrian Pavilion, designed by Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 World's Fair in Brussels, is a famous example of modern post-war architecture with its simple shapes, glass halls, bold which expressed a belief in technological progress.
Schwanzer's Pavilion won the Architecture Grand Prix in 1958 for its lightweight soaring steel and glass structure.
The building is considered a milestone in modern architecture.
This made the architect so famous that he also built the Austrian pavilion at the next World's Fair.
He eventually rose to fame around the world in 1973 with his legendary BMW four-cylinder tower and her sister, the bowl-shaped building.
The pavilion, conceived as a temporary exhibition building, was moved to the Swiss Garden near Vienna's South Station, converted and opened as the 20th Century Museum in 1962 - and is often referred to as the "House of the 20th Century" for this reason.
In any case, the building was not suitable for the museum for technical and spatial reasons - there were no walls on which to hang works of art, and poor air conditioning.
However, it continued to be used until modern art in Vienna got a new home.
The house had been empty since 2001, and his condition was getting worse and worse.
Architect Adolf Krishanitz has now renovated the pavilion, which has been named “21st Century House” and will be used as a museum of contemporary art.
This museum, a branch of the Belvedere Museum, which will open its first exhibition on Tuesday evening, is a joyous event in every sense.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Belvedere Gallery in 2007, contributed to the new venture.
Husslein-Arco, a graduate of the Faculty of Art History with a brilliant career as a figure skater in her youth who worked at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and eventually became the founder and director of the Museum of Modernity in Salzburg, convinced politicians and curators to continue the reconstruction, attracted public funds and private donations and made a decision on how the building would be used.
The new museum was to accommodate a permanent exhibition of the Fritz Votruba Foundation, a cafe and a bookstore along with contemporary art. An office building was also to be built.
Strict Control & Limited Budget
Krishanitz was then the ideal candidate for the project.
He was known, of course, for the restoration and expansion of the Vienna Secession by Josef Olbrich, and won the competition, but he also studied with Schwanzer at the Vienna University of Technology, and the pavilion was for him "an exceptionally important place" where he attended exhibitions "almost every week".
He knew the original design and knew the tasks that stood in front of the building, a building that had already lost some of its grandeur and ease when it was moved to Vienna and converted.
The problems that arose in the last restructuring were much more serious. The building was a "energy absorber," Krishanitz says.
The window profiles on the glass facade were replaced, a glass-enhanced safety glass was inserted, and the glass roof was replaced by a high-strength safety glass.
The steel bars of the heat bridge were reinforced or replaced, and asbestos was removed from the ceilings.
The two lower floors have created space for new use of the building, a fallen light well between the building and the street provides lighting - a virtually new building but still an elegant Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors were preserved and the building was painted in the old red-brown color of corrosion protection.
The cinema hall is the same as it used to be.
All this under strict control of the museum management and with a limited budget.
“We often had to find material that was good, cheap and would be approved by the museum management,” Krishanitz says, pointing to the uneven flooring in the basement.
The building remained flexible and light despite limitations, challenges and transformations.
Krishanitz noted recently that the pavilion "from Brussels" was rough - a typical history of "drops in the city".
Such an architecture is “always out of place” and yet wants to “stimulate real awareness.”
The house of the 21st century is in a very right place, as unexpected luck has happened when planning the city. A completely redesigned "main station quarter" with offices and residential real estate grows around the Swiss Garden.
A second happy event may occur. The 21st century house may be complemented by a second Krishanitz building - collector Francesca von Habsburg has acquired the Berlin Temporary Exhibition Hall and is reportedly in talks with the city about its location next door in the Swiss Garden.
