7 Lessons From Steve Jobs' Lost Interview Shown In Theater This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, describing the technical genius as the Great Inventor of Modernity.
But what Apple fans might consider the biggest revelation in the newly discovered interview, which was recalled ahead of previews in major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about business processes and manufacturing technologies.
He was, of course, a designer, a dreamer, and considered himself a hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and modernizationist of the production process, who believed that many business executives suffered from "the pain of thinking that a really great idea makes up 90 percent of the work... [but] a great idea from a great product separates a huge amount of skillful labor."
Back in 1995, Bob Kringley created the television series Triumph of the Nerds about the appearance of a personal computer, and he spent more than an hour with Jobs for a unique long conversation.
By that time, about 10 years had passed since Jobs was kicked out of Apple, and he was already working hard at his new computer company NeXT in anticipation of the mass adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Kringley's interview was used in the Nerds, he says the originals of the interview went missing during transportation.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full VHS copy was found in the director's garage.
This footage, slightly edited, became the basis for the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which airs at Landmark Theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For a man known for his hatred of in-depth interviews, Jobs seems unusually willing to state his technological philosophy and business strategy here.
And incredibly thoughtful.
In four different moments during the interview, there are large intervals between questions and answers - reflections of 10-15 seconds, where Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts to be more precise.
There are also moments where Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface where he seems annoyed by Kringley’s questions, forcing him to move more quickly to issues or phenomena of greater importance.
The Lost Interview is something ominously prophetic when Jobs evaluates what he sees different companies doing right and wrong and offers his own vision for the future of information technology.
It's one thing to read about Jobs' posthumous evaluations, but there's something vulnerable and inspiring about Jobs that we see here, an anxious dreamer on the verge of greatness.
He has a vision of what things could and should be.
Shortly after he said everything here, he went and did it.
A brief summary of the seven significant findings of the Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"Throughout my time in business, I kept asking, 'Why are you doing this?' and the answers you invariably get are, 'Oh, it's just done that way.'
No one knows why they do what they do, no one thinks in business very deeply.
That's what I found out.
Jobs continues to detail his efforts to rationalize reporting at Apple.
Frustrated with a way of recording costs, often starting with “standard costs” that were taken from the ceiling and then adjusted using “clarification”, he created an automated structure that ensured that they could track business costs down to the smallest detail.
A joke about the Pope:
Jobs talks in detail about the “blue box” he made with Steve Wozniak, a device that allowed people to hack into the phone company effectively and make long-distance calls for free.
A lot has been written about the device before, but Jobs’ euphoria here when describing the blue box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He tells how he and Wozniak tested the box using a payphone, ordering a conversation and then connecting from one AT&T network to another until they connected as many stations as possible.
“We covered the globe half a dozen times, and you were screaming at the pay phone, and it was infiltrating a minute later into a nearby pay phone,” Jobs says with a grin.
“We were young, and all we learned was that we could build something that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
The two of us knew a little bit, but we could make a little thing that could control a big thing — it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple could ever have come along without it.
Jobs goes on to describe in detail one famous antics he and Wozniak had practically dealt with by calling the Vatican through the blue box at midnight and asking the Pope to call, struggling to copy Henry Kissinger.
When various members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak to an American diplomat, the two burst out laughing just before the Pope himself was picked up to answer the phone.
On falling in love with technology (and the cold nickname of Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to assemble a frequency meter, he found Bill Hewlett in the telephone directory and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
“It had a strong impact on me, it was the only company I saw at that age, and it shaped my view of what a company is and how well they treat their employees.”
Jobs later became one of HP’s employees who visited the company’s Palo Alto research labs, where he saw “the very first desktop computer.”
He was the size of a suitcase, he had a small monitor with an electron beam tube, and I fell in love with him.
I used to go to HP as a teenager and spin around that car and write programs for it.
Improvised innovation:
In several interviews, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the fly.
At the dawn of his career, when he went to sell a handful of circuit boards, one buyer asked him to assemble a whole computer.
Working only 30 days on credit, he had to think over both the assembly and delivery of ready-made devices.
Later at Apple, he recalls the difficulties he faced while developing a computer mouse:
"I remember the fierce arguments... they shouted at me that it would take five years [to assemble a mouse that would cost $300] and I was fed up and came out and found a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we were able to raise for $15, which was incredibly reliable.
Companies that are losing energy:
Long before he spearheaded Apple’s resurgence, Jobs foresaw exactly how many industry leaders would go wrong in their vision and lose control of their market share.
“Let’s say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make the best copier or printer, and what?”
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company does not become more successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [these are] the types of people who end up leading companies and the people making the product are pushed out of the decision-making platform.
The genius of the product that led to this monopolistic position is supplanted by people who have no idea of the difference between good and bad products - the required skill.
This is what happened to Xerox.
Xerox could take over the entire information technology industry.
He could have been ten times bigger, he could have been a Microsoft of the '90s.
They were defeated by victory.
Innovation as an art form:
“A great idea is separated from a great product by a great amount of skillful labor... when you promote a great idea, it changes and grows.”
You’ll learn a lot about its intricacies.
There are compromises you need to make - some things you won't be able to make electrons, glass, robots or factories do.
You need to keep 5,000 ideas in your head - these concepts - connecting them all together...
Ultimately, it all comes down to taste — it all comes down to trying to express yourself at the best that humans have ever produced, and later trying to bring that into what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We have always been ashamed to steal great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh famous was that the people who worked on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who happened to be the best information technology specialists in the world.
If it weren’t for information technology, they would be doing amazing things in other areas.
