Stories of cheating in school and college exams are common.
There were cases when teachers gave students answers to the tests in order to have a good assessment of the results of their activities.
Mentors who have to teach the opposite send a message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How many lies are we facing?
During one day, studies show that you can lie 10 to 200 times.
Much of this is now believed to be a lie for salvation.
Another study found that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes they met each other.
Identifying lies or incriminating lies is a necessary skill for everyone, both for personal and professional purposes.
Unlike a room game similar to, say, a charade where you have to exclaim "Fucked!", lie detection is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific evidence gathered over the past six decades at prestigious universities engaged in comprehensive research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One result of the study is that most of the old myths about lies have been debunked.
The liars look in the eyes.
They do not always stutter, stutter, blush or fuss.
It is not necessary to conclude from this that liars are difficult to notice and difficult to expose.
An experienced liar can get to the truth by observing the structure of statements, facial expressions, the structure of questions and time characteristics.
I’ve spent several years researching scientific discoveries in a vast and ever-growing segment of lie knowledge, and it’s clear that lying detection is a modern skill that’s easy to learn and helps navigate in our complex world — especially if your professional responsibilities include recruiting, interviewing, negotiating, or managing.
Good liars are excellent at reading others, making them feel at ease, managing their own emotions and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men lie more about themselves, while women lie more about others, usually to protect someone else’s feelings that married people lie less to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they say are most often brazen).
We also know that if you are perceived as a cheater, others will feel less guilty about cheating on you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your object.
This is called "defining the initial state."
This helps provide a starting point for assessing changes further.
Observe the posture, laughter, voice characteristics of your object.
It would be good for you to know if a person is constantly tapping with their feet in a normal state, then you will not make unfair accusations when you see a kicking in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for groups of deceptive verbal and nonverbal actions.
Treat these groups as red flags, not proof of deception.
Deceivers can fix the top of their body when trying to remember their story, they can put their feet towards the door, lean toward the exit, change their posture in a certain way, or show "relief after an interview" -- this exaggerated sigh of relief and a change of posture when all the difficult questions are over.
Investigators often falsify the end-of-examination signal just to look at this relief after the interview.
So, pay attention to the speech of your object.
Scott Peterson is known to have stumbled on and used the past tense, claiming his murdered wife is alive, leading to her search across the country.
Adverse people can also use distance in speech: "I didn't have a sexual relationship with this woman ... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat the difficult question completely.
The most typical verbal indicators are barely perceptible.
Someone can use “qualification language” when answering a difficult question: “Okay ... in truth ... as far as I know ... as far as I know”.
This makes the answer more emotional than actual, and is often a red flag.
There is no magic means to detect lies, but you can master the skill of detecting deception.
These skills will increase the chances of everyone not to become a victim of skillful scammers in professional and personal life.
