The decline in economic activity caused, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, during the first three quarters there was an accelerated increase in the unemployment rate, from January to March 55.053 residents of Sinaloa were unemployed, with a share of 4.53% of the economically active population, in the second quarter the share increased to 5.28 percent, and from July to September it continued to grow to 6.19%, a share that is more than the number of people.
Reduced liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is tainted by many factors, for economist Gerardo Lopez Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the Autonomous University (UAS), the rise in unemployment can be explained indirectly, by actions that were taken in public policy.
“What we are seeing now is an increase in unemployment, which is due to several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market in order to limit the resources imposed by the law that was passed in Congress to combat money laundering, since it is difficult for people who illegally own dollars to work with them, invest and use them in something,” he said.
Stopped immigration
Lopez Cervantes said there is also a demographic factor in the rise in unemployment.
“The number of people who leave the state in search of work abroad in the United States was limited, primarily because of difficulties with entry, and the second because once they entered, they already face many difficulties in finding work, so that a group of people stay and demand jobs here in the state, as a result, the unemployment rate increases,” he said.
Violation of formal requirements
Sinaloa’s labor market analysis is worse when you look at the large number of violations that prevail in working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the active population of the state works without being mentioned as workers in any social protection institution.
In addition to unemployment and malpractice, another reminder of working in the state is represented by low wages; the state has the lowest wages in the country, according to records from the Mexican Social Security Institute and the Ministry of Labor and Social Welfare.
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers was 5,352 pesos until September, well below the national average of 7,375 pesos.
Reduction of FDI
In addition to the decline in economic activity and high unemployment, 2011 saw the largest outflow of foreign direct investment in the past 10 years, according to the Ministry of Finance, from January to July the state’s FDI stood at $630,697, a drop of 87.74 percent compared to $5,143,312 during the same period last year.
For its part, the State Government’s Ministry of Economic Development recorded just 17,280,000 pesos of investment during the year, which mainly fell on service companies.
Debt
Amid the economic downturn, the state government asked the state Congress in July to approve a 3 billion peso loan that would be used to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 municipalities to revive the economy, only 2,600 million pesos were approved locally, and until November, no sector of the state’s economy was expected to benefit from the debt.
Reactions
For business representatives, the first year of the government of Mario Lopez Valdés demonstrates the lack of government capabilities.
Miguel Loredo Lopez, president of the National Chamber of Manufacturing, said that during 2011 there was a lack of agreement on the wishes of various sectors, including the state government itself.
“The efficiency of the economy in Sinaloa this year was really low, we have to work hard to regain the positions lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble our efforts, we have not been able to coordinate the efforts of everyone and, above all, the good and synchronized work of the new government team, we hope that next year will be much better,” he said.
Slowdown of the economy
Lopez Loredo said events such as early frosts this year had stalled the state's economy and its efficiency and growth were limited.
“Low volumes of the economy are the result of several events, including frost, one of the main effects was a slow economy that does not become fast enough to create economic dynamics that allow us to have an acceptable level of processes, goods and services and, therefore, at the end of the year we close it below our expectations,” he said.
Revision of direction
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Employers of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, said the state needs to continue the most dynamic production activity.
“Overall, we found that we were working on it, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that will redefine the direction and economic course of the state, it is necessary to mobilize all the material and human resources that Sinaloa has,” he said.
Work to be undertaken
The president of Coparmex stressed the importance of determining the future direction in order to better guide the government’s efforts.
“In general, I would say that the Government is trying to be successful in various areas, in terms of economic development there is little progress, but it is important to develop a long-term program,” he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in its own manner of public policy.
“There are facts that allow us to say that the government is starting to get involved in the work and that I can say that some work has been done and I think the government is aware that there is still a lot of work to be done,” he said.
