A new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday.
The appointed prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the Italian president to introduce a new government that will face a crisis that has put the country on the brink of economic disaster.
Italian Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet on Wednesday with the Italian president to introduce a new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and hurt the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace said Monty, who is scheduled to meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday, would confirm that he could form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, though it is unclear when the new executive will take its positions.
Monty said he would present the president with the results of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
“I want to reaffirm my full confidence in the ability of our country to get out of this difficult period,” the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monty did not say directly that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that the obstacles had been overcome.
“The structure is now well defined,” he said.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than usual, as Italy struggled with a political and financial crisis that brought their debt to a critical level.
The administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve the austerity package demanded by European leaders to restore confidence in Italy.
At the heart of the pressure on Monty to hasten, volatile markets have set Italy’s BTP bond yield at 10 years above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to bail out.
Emma Marchegaglia, leader of the Italian Federation of Employers, told reporters after meeting with Monti, "We have said that we will actively support this government."
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this critical situation.
Monti's chances of success were largely based on the support of the LDP party Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday due to the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts should lead to a good outcome," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centrist-right party, told reporters.
The support of the LDP, the largest party in Italy, is significant because until now many of its members have opposed the government majority consisting of technocrats who form Monti.
Parliamentary support
The new Monty government should have strong parliamentary support for reforms that will likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blocking or suspension of these attempts could lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has stepped up pressure, warning that Monty's failure could be a disaster.
Monty began his consultations Monday with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as youth and women's organizations.
He will end his series of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monty was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who authorized an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi will resign, the cost of Italy’s debts has now reached a critical level amid uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will be successful.
Saving Italy with a public debt of 1.8 billion euros would be too much for the modern financial defenders of the eurozone.
Monty said his government would exist until the next election, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians would only give him time to carry out reforms before calling a new election.
Monty said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the main parties insist that it should be composed only of technical specialists, evidence of their dissatisfaction with the fact that the financial situation affects the process.
Political sources reported that mutual distrust and disagreement between parties made it more difficult to include political figures.
