MSS Announces Obesity Gene Search Program
Social protection leads research into obesity gene in children and young adults; it is supported by experts from IPN
The Mexican Institute of Social Protection (MSSI) announced that it is conducting a study to detect the obesity gene in children and young people, which is called the Protocol “Genetics of obesity in childhood and adolescence”, which will provide a count of signs associated with overweight.
In a statement, Miguel Cruz Lopez, head of the Division of Medical Research in Biochemistry of the Specialized Hospital of the National Medical Center of the XXI Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was assembled.
This team is assisted by specialists and graduate students of the National Institute of Health of the Nation (NIPH) and the Center for Scientific Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
In the study, the population (prescribed or not) is invited to participate by going to the MSSI sports centers participating in the study, in the Valley of Mexico, where tests involving children will be conducted every Saturday, from 8:00 am.
He stressed that the protocol began to be kept in the sports center in Cuautemok (in the west of Mexico state), and since October 8, events have been held in the sports center in Nesaualcoyotl (east of Mexico state).
Once the goal of attracting between 500 and 600 children is met, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Center (south of Mexico City) and finally at the Morelos Sports Center (north of Mexico City).
He explained that the purpose of this study is to understand the components and importance of genetics in relation to the development of obesity and to establish a risk factor among children and young Mexicans to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On November 14, World Diabetes Day will be celebrated, and the main goal is to gather three thousand children and adolescents aged 6 to 14 years with the permission of parents and under their supervision to fill out individual nutrition questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and the history of familial hereditary diseases to avoid risk factors that lead to diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that anthropometric measurements of all participants (weight, height and waist circumference), blood pressure and glucose, fat, cholesterol and insulin levels, and genetic analysis (to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity) would be performed on Saturday.
Cruz Lopez said that this study reflects the concern of health care professionals about the alarming weight gain among children.
Medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006 show that in just 6 years, there was an increase: in the case of boys, 77 percent were obese, in the case of girls, 47 percent; in terms of excess weight, there was also a significant increase,” said the MSSI specialist.
He said that the validity of the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from other peoples in its genetic history.
He reported that, on average, the Mexican is 65 percent American Indian, 30 percent European, and five percent African, a condition that affects genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that the main consequence of the genetics of obesity is the body’s inability to burn excess energy that we consume (calories), and it is deposited as fat.
The researcher explained that the immediate benefit to the participants is a comprehensive assessment of the children, which can reveal whether they have at least some degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark folds on the neck (acants) and forearms means the likelihood of metabolic disorders and even prediabetes.
The information is treated with all confidentiality, doctors transmit it in writing to parents, to whom they explain all measurements and changes in lifestyle that must be taken to avoid the disease.
Cruz Lopez explained that there are three main causes of overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle, or lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day at home in front of the TV and using transport at short distances instead of walking.
This is also due to high calorie intake, that is, an increase in the consumption of sugary drinks and carbohydrates (tamale, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and genetic predisposition, analyzed in this program.
Asphalt UNAM will be able to avoid cracks
Rafael Herrera, a researcher in the UNAM chemistry department, developed polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of the best quality, resistant to environmental influences and temperature.
If the signals sent by the road surface were given attention, it would be necessary to repair about 200 thousand pits for each rainy season in the metropolitan area in the Valley of Mexico, says Rafael Herrera Nahera, researcher of the chemical faculty of UNAM, and adds that if the process of construction and content of asphalted road surface is correct, the number of pits can be reduced or even reduced to zero.
In his lecture The Technological View of the Pits, read as part of the International Year of Chemistry, it is reported that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture with characteristics close to bitumen, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nahera said this type of modified bitumen can be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and therefore counteract pit formation.
He explained that bitumen, the heaviest part of oil, is a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight called maltens, which together give the road surface its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of bitumen is the fact that at high temperatures of about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120, its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius, it retains an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the bitumen becomes fragile, he said.
This means that street asphalt resistance is not constant, but varies throughout the day, depending on natural conditions and temperature, said a specialist in chemical engineering.
He noticed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered with a flexible coating, which is made up of six layers of material, of which the last three include bitumen.
Among the uppermost layers is the bitumen, made up of small stones lowered into the bitumen and then compressed.
Every stone that makes up this coating, he said, is immersed in bitumen.
When moving vehicles and applying effort, it helps forces to be very well distributed over the road surface.
If it were a modified asphalt, they would distribute even better, said a chemical engineer.
On the asphalt pavement, he added, is placed the last layer, which is called the wear layer, which is made of fine stone, in fact sand is also immersed in asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will come into contact with the wheels of transport, it should have more resistance than asphalt coating and provide road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and distribute this effort, the wear layer also requires proper thickness, and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the condition of the asphalt.
When the ground is raw, the water penetrates the coating and it is difficult for it to get out of there, this causes the softening of all layers of the coating and, consequently, the formation of pits.
In the formation of pits, he said, the first wear layer and only then it affects the bitumen, but the damage does not occur instantly, this process should be paid attention at the first signs of maintenance programs.
Also, a member of the National System of Researchers explained that transport load is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each layer of coating should always be associated with transport load and it is necessary to ensure that this requirement is met to prevent the frequent occurrence of pits.
Rafael Herrera said that there is still a lot to learn about bitumen and do, for example, bitumen emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries and even help to repair pits with ease and without using high temperatures.
