Energy policy:
Facts must prevail over dogmas.
If there is a topic that cannot be decided after a short discussion or under the influence of emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affects the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is a healthy trend that election meetings become a reason to reflect on the share and place occupied by nuclear energy.
The dispute will not bear fruit until all the economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options are examined.
France must base its opinion on objective facts and rational data.
With 7,000 million people on the planet, demographic development will double the need for electricity by 2050, unless a huge portion of the world’s population is deprived of vital elements.
During the same period, it will become necessary to fill the growing shortage of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity constantly, not forgetting the crucial need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat the climate imbalance - a topic that has disappeared from the environmental debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these factors.
That is why Germany is left alone in its decision to abandon nuclear energy.
This is not the case in Belgium, which has made its decision dependent on the need to find a source capable of replacing nuclear energy, or Switzerland, which intends to build only the most modern reactors.
On the other hand, the UK, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil are just a few of those who are resolutely continuing their projects.
The United States decided after Fukushima to add one plant to its kit, resuming construction of the station, which was interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
Although Germany’s renewable energy model is sometimes cited as an example, reality contradicts this argument.
The choice of Berlin will result in an increase in the cost of electricity, increased energy dependence, exacerbated by the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, a jump in carbon dioxide emissions in connection with the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, all these unpleasant effects will already be felt.
The example of Denmark should be considered.
The European champion for turbine construction, from which it receives 30% of its electricity, it is also the largest consumer of coal and gas due to intermittent wind; due to which carbon dioxide emissions and electricity prices are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the other hand, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbors pay 40% more for electricity than French households.
Since in a globalized economy the price of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and the key to maintaining industrial equipment in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in nuclear power will lead to a large increase in the cost of electricity, which will make illusory beautiful statements about the new industrialization of our country and the protection of purchasing power.
The price that most French people refuse to pay, especially because they do not object to this type of energy in principle.
It should be remembered that the country’s energy policy made it possible to create an industry of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 indirect ones.
Highly export-oriented, it attracts a whole galaxy of internationally specialized small and medium-sized enterprises and creates many jobs that cannot be moved to another industry.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would have to sacrifice a large number of these enterprises and lose 6 thousand million euros per year from French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrical engineer would order an EPR designed to last sixty years if its manufacturer was scheduled to close?
To solve the energy equation, we must recognize that there are no divine or diabolical sources of energy production.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is undoubtedly a vital issue.
In France, we have a security body that carries out uncompromising and transparent control of existing energy centers, such as Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is universally recognized, are full of the same security obsession.
Over the past 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious incidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions, but with no consequences for humans or the environment.
At Chernobyl, the reactor arrangement and unforgivable human error led to the tragedy.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident occurred as a result of two natural disasters of unprecedented force, which resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it learned from the previous two.
The fruit of this step and the cooperation between the security agencies, operators and French and German designers, EPR, presents a project to counter such phenomena.
Since it is considered by all energy professionals wishing to build a reactor, stopping its construction in Flamanville will be a great gift to Areva and EDF competitors, clearing the way for them to gain leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is necessary and legitimate to look for the best combination of energy sources for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotions, dogmas and biased maneuvers to prevail in a dispute that is so important for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or a boon to the economy?
Nicolas Sarkozy's immigration policies have been criticized on various fronts - the overload of police, judicial and administrative services, subordinated to the policy figures and the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of France as a "human rights state".
Then there was the administrative harassment of foreign students, which got into the news when the Minister of Internal Affairs (Liberation, May 23) said that France “does not need foreign talents, masons and waiters.”
But it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
The left and right agree on this point.
The right-wing tone was set by Jacques Chirac, who in 1976 declared that "900,000 unemployed will not be a problem in a country with 2 million foreign workers", and the left-wing by Michel Rocard, who explained in 1990 that France "cannot accept the poor from around the world".
The only difference is the level of generosity.
In 2005, the fear of invasion of the country by the hordes of Polish plumbers was felt by both the left and right.
Both sides see immigration as a burden on the French economy and on French society.
The only difference is the level of generosity that they will allow to show to immigrants.
In his program, Francois Hollande limited himself to platitudes, saying that “joint work will solve our immigration problem.”
This notion of immigration as a burden and a problem can give an electoral advantage, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Jeffrey Cameron remind us in a recent book summarizing the latest data on immigration (Special People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Shape Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among professionals about the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages, and employment in countries that host immigrants.
Restriction of immigration leads to a weakening of growth and reduces employment.
Fears of immigrant influence are based on the notion that they can replace local workers, especially low-skilled ones, by provoking lower wages.
But experience shows that in reality, immigrants are far more complementary than replacing the local workforce by doing jobs that lack the local workforce.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract local labor, and the most skilled - in dynamic sectors where training is not associated with job offers.
Positive impact on salaries
Just as it would be difficult for a surgeon to work in a country where there is a shortage of anaesthetists, the complementarity existing between local and immigrant workers leads to the fact that the arrival of immigrants has a positive effect on the wages of local workers.
Giovanni Peri estimated that a 1% increase in migration flow leads to a 0.6-0.9% increase in real long-term wages.
And this is without taking into account the fact that the diversity introduced by immigrants contributes to the creation of new ideas and economic growth (among American Nobel laureates, a large proportion of naturalized immigrants, and Google, Intel, Paypal and Yahoo were all founded by immigrants).
Migrants also bring net profit to social security systems, giving an average of 1% of the total budgets of European countries.
According to the World Labor Organization, for example, in Germany, an immigrant, arriving at the age of 30, will bring the state budget a net profit (income minus expenses) on average 150 000 euros during his life.
Nicolas Sarkozy at the beginning of his mandate was going to “teeth” to cling to the missing points of growth.
These teeth, which were used to scare off immigrants, gave exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it remains to comprehend European democracy
Democracy is a valuable acquisition, but at the same time fragile.
The European continent must remember that, having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, in the 20th century it survived the tragedies of World War I, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, Gulag, as well as Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and colonels in Greece.
Some believed that in order for democracy to finally triumph over its enemies, it is enough to arrange a vote and make it as direct as possible.
Since the days of Napoleon "Little" it is known that this comes from the superficiality of thinking.
Universal suffrage, although a prerequisite for democracy, is not a sufficient condition for it and may even become a "tool of suppression", as the Republican philosopher Etienne Washro once said.
No, democracy requires much more - public space, public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of powers, education, enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The European crisis we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but above all it is a political crisis and a crisis of democracy.
In this respect, the palinody of a truthfully false Greek referendum will have a double-debunking effect, demonstrating both the need for a serious change of policy and the unpleasant feeling of its impossibility and inconsistency.
This duality needs to be understood in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front line of the struggle for democracy has now shifted and, according to many, Republican soldiers are now aiming in the wrong direction.
We will gain nothing by demanding a series of national referenda, organized as necessary and in a chaotic manner.
"Carte blanche" for an absolute European monarch or a jump with bound legs into the abyss of nationalism - what a choice for a citizen!
No, we do not dream of a guillotine blade, but of a common, clear and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at the pan-European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal, and it is unknown how many more of them will have to be listed, because there is only one crisis - the crisis of Europe.
The whole of Europe obeys the dictates of markets and rating agencies, suffers from its weakness and from a lack of solidarity.
The whole of Europe is completely humiliated on the international stage.
Many worry about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but all of Europe is gradually losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
It is urgent to return the management of the European project under people’s sovereignty.
Because only by working together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of everyone’s debts, free themselves from markets and prepare for the future by investing in it.
Recovering from the crisis will require decisions at the pan-European level, and they cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, without leading us to disaster.
After a long discussion of this proposal by the socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone now demands a European economic government.
That's it.
But to imagine it without a stronger economic, political and democratic integration that has come to life is another madness and a new impasse.
We need to start a new phase of European construction.
To establish a republic in France, it was necessary to “create” Republicans.
A revolution of interest would not be enough.
This lesson remains valid.
We must build a Europe that is united on an economic level.
This can only be done by creating a more democratic Europe on a political level, a real people’s European sovereignty.
To create Europe, let’s create Europeans.
