Paris is concerned about the ties of the Islamic Maghreb with the Boko Haram sect.
Long-held links between the al-Qaeda terrorist group in the Muslim Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect Boko Haram have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algeria’s deputy foreign minister Abdelkader Messahel even said Algerians were now confident.
“The way these two organizations are used and the reports from the secret services show that they are actively cooperating,” he explained, without going into details.
Paris seems to have reached similar conclusions.
An investigation into the kidnapping of two French nationals in Niger in January identified two links.
Kidnapped at a restaurant in Niamey by people close to Aqmi, Antoine de Leocour and Vincent Delory were apparently killed the next day along with several of the kidnappers during an operation conducted by French special forces.
Among the remains of the operation, French and Nigerian investigators found several SIM cards belonging to terrorists.
The Axis of Terror
The analysis of the calls indicated several interlocutors in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), investigators are particularly interested in two numbers; one points to a Nigerian who has long lived in Maidiguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man allegedly close to Aqmi and a sect.
“This is a step forward, but we certainly have to wait for more reliable evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram.”
"But it's possible."
“It has been known for many years that the sect is receiving financial and ideological support from outside and that it is becoming more and more active,” says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
