Nord Stream, a new gateway for Russian gas to Europe.
The Nord Stream gas pipeline connecting Western Europe and Russia directly along the bottom of the Baltic Sea has been launched.
It is designed to supply the equivalent of 30 million households with gas.
Gazprom, Russia’s giant gas producer, wanted to celebrate the event with pomp.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part last Tuesday on the shores of the Baltic, between an orchestra performance and gourmet snacks, in the opening of Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia and Germany under water.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Francois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mart Rutte together turned the symbolic valve controlling the flow of Russian gas into the Western European network.
Through the new gas pipeline, 27.5 million additional cubic meters of gas will be supplied to Western Europe every year through the first pipeline with a length of 1,224 km, connecting the Leningrad region with the land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
The second pipeline is expected to be ready by the end of 2012, delivering a total of 55,000 million cubic meters of gas equivalent to France’s entire consumption.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline in the same direction is already being discussed.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project is a victory.
The project met with fierce resistance from Poland and the Baltic states.
Nord Stream will indeed allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries will lose some of their power: they will find it harder to influence Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the most tense moment of the debate, Warsaw did not stop before comparing the Nord Stream with the new "German-Soviet Pact", hinting at an alliance between Hitler and Stalin with the aim of occupying Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically sensitive.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe seeks greater security of its supplies.
But at the cost of depriving Europe of energy, because the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europe.
In less than five years, Russia has managed to achieve its understanding of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries that consume large volumes of gas and whose own reserves are already running out.
"This gas pipeline is part of cooperation with Russia, it is a new artery that organically connects us," Francois Fillon said, opening the pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large gas contracts are important both politically and economically.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the heads of Gazprom, who were present in large numbers in Lubmin, the point of arrival of gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel enclosed in concrete to protect it from ship anchors.
It lies at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 meters.
To build it, it was necessary to bypass the minefields left from the Second World War.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," said Jens Mueller, a spokesman for the Nord Stream company.
It was also necessary to take many steps to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipeline is a long metal snake weighing 242 Eiffel Towers, with no breaks along its entire length, no valves, and no service stations.
The control platform was planned in the area of Sweden, but the project managers refused it, because Sweden was not happy with the fact that the Russian state-owned company will permanently settle off its shores.
“In the event of an accident, we will cut off the flow of gas in less than a minute,” says Jens Muller.
So, in case of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline will go into the air.
But this seems unlikely to designers who have designed seams designed to leak only once every 100,000 years.
Control over the condition of the pipeline will be carried out by an underwater robot, which pulls the ship, for external observation, as well as a device circulating inside the pipeline.
The cigar-shaped apparatus is inserted into the pipeline with a diameter of 1 meter and pushed forward by a stream of gas.
Upon arrival after 3 full days of traveling at a speed of 3 meters per second, it gives accurate information about any deformation of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without the need for the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is carried out only due to its pressure.
It is 200 bar on departure and 100 bar on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which owns 51% of the capital.
The rest are German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), Dutch Gasunie and French Group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies set up a joint venture called Nord Stream, which was tasked with building and operating the pipeline.
Its headquarters are in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favorable.
Then Gazprom leased this company for twenty years with the possibility of extending the entire volume of gas transportation.
“Gazprom will pay for the full volume, regardless of how much gas will actually be transported,” says Jens Muller.
Financing for the construction of the gas pipeline was provided by 30% of shareholders and 70% of bank loans.
The total cost of the works will be 7.4 thousand euros for two pipelines.
GDF Suez will invest about 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will pay back their costs, because Gazprom takes all the risks.
The gas pipeline exits the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy shore planted with coniferous trees.
The 4.5-meter-high vents form the outlet terminal of the gas.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas before pumping it into German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of gas every hour.
At full capacity it will be 3 million per hour, and in 2012 6 million.
Moleskine Brand Notebook
Moleskine, created by an Italian company fifteen years ago, will return the taste for writing.
He has the scent of adventure, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easy to recognize by its rectangular black cover, by its rubber band, by its yellowish-white pages, as if yellowed over time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, located in Milan, decided to launch designer notebooks for sale.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, took responsibility for launching the new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old technique of production, moleskin - varnished cotton fabric, used, for example, to cover the benches.
This type of notebook is said to be highly appreciated by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has brought an old and forgotten thing that was iconic for avant-garde artists until the 20th century into line with today's taste," said Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the managing brand at Modo Modo.
Success has come.
From 2006 to 2010, sales increased by 25% and reached 12.7 million units.
We are far from the production of the first years, when only 3000 notebooks were produced.
Moleskine crossed the borders of Italy and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish the profile of a typical buyer, because a notebook equally attracts a businessman, a student and a person of a free profession.
Moleskine buyers are cosmopolitan, have broad views and are educated.
The small Italian company, which initially had only 12 employees, now has 100 and two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in Fnac bookstores, shops in the centers of small towns and was able to gain wide popularity.
“We have followed the spirit of the times and this new need for writing despite the advent of email,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This characteristic cultural feature accompanies the development of Moleskine; recently, the brand organized an exhibition "Around the Way", where architects and artists demonstrated their own notebooks.
In August, he also launched a leopard painting cover for the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products, which now include bags, pens, computer bags. The brand includes all kinds of support.
The success that gave rise to envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, which wrote a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week of employment for people with disabilities begins today.
Despite the policy of public charity launched in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average, namely 19 per cent against 9 per cent for the general population.
Disappointing?
“No,” emphasizes Eric Blanche, CEO of Adapt, an organization that organizes a week of employment for people with disabilities.
“Over the last 15 years, significant progress has been made.”
At that time, the share of the unemployed was not 2 but 3 times more.
“But there is still a lot of work to do.”
I must say that there are still many obstacles to employment for the disabled.
Among them, there are more elderly: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They are more likely to have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor’s degree, and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very common, which is 85% for people with disabilities, against 38% on average.
In short, these are all criteria that make it very difficult to return to work and that are at the heart of the problem,” said Christian Grapen, CEO of Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There is no need to talk about a mentality that is changing, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association commissioned by Cité found that the managers surveyed had a low level of knowledge about disability and "represented complete people in wheelchairs or mentally or mentally impaired."
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from the goal of having 6% of disabled workers set by a law passed in 1987.
The last known figures, dating back to 2008, give a value of 2.6%.
“Today we are about 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the organization responsible for collecting tax from companies that do not comply with this law.
Proof: The number of “taxable” organizations, as well as the amounts paid, decreased from 59,000 to 46,000 in 2007-2011 (and from 606 million to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law that raised the tax put a lot of pressure on companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects an increase in consciousness, particularly in large enterprises.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of organizations with 20 to 49 employees have disabled employees, compared to 82% of organizations with 100 to 199.
